<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / International Company News: Flotation values Dutch telecoms
at Fl 22.9bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A first tranche of shares in Koninklijke PTT Nederland, the state-owned
Dutch postal and telecommunications operator, will be floated next week at a
price of Fl 49.75 per share, valuing the company at Fl 22.9bn (Dollars
12.3bn).
The price is slightly higher than many analysts had predicted, and just
above the mid-point of the indicative range of Fl 46 to Fl 52 a share.
Private investors will be given a discount of Fl 2.50 per share on up to 75
shares. This is in line with the government's commitment to give small
shareholders a discount of around 5 per cent compared with the price paid by
institutional investors.
The flotation of 138.15m shares, representing 30 per cent of the
government's 100 per cent holding in KPN, will raise Fl 6.9bn for the state.
An additional Fl 1bn could be generated if the banking syndicate exercises
its 30-day right to sell a further 20.7m shares in case of heavy
oversubscription.
Analysts had agreed the flotation price would be Fl 50 or less, with many
predicting Fl 48 or Fl 49. The government is aiming to sell half the shares
in the Netherlands.
The price, announced yesterday morning, was determined early on Sunday. It
was based on the outcome of a 'book-building' exercise among institutional
investors. Subscriptions opened yesterday and will close on Thursday
afternoon. Trading on the Amsterdam stock exchange is due to start on
Monday.
Mr Wim Kok, the finance minister, said yesterday the transaction should give
'a substantial stimulus to the strengthening and deepening of the Dutch
capital market'. The stock exchange hopes the KPN example will persuade
privately- or family-owned companies in the Netherlands to seek bourse
listings.
KPN's total market capitalisation will make it the third-largest stock on
the Amsterdam stock exchange, behind the two Anglo-Dutch groups Royal
Dutch/Shell and Unilever. The flotation, which is to be followed with a
second tranche by the end of 1997, is the Netherlands' largest.
The KPN flotation is the fifth European telecoms share offering in the past
year, but the first privatisation of a state monopoly to include a postal
service.
The UK government will soon launch a consultation paper likely to advocate
partial privatisation of the Royal Mail. Part of the case for the move is
the need for the state operator to be able to compete internationally with
more entrepreneurial postal services, notably the Dutch.
</TEXT>
