<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Intercare interim results hit by changes in
Dutch legislation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REG VAUGHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dutch legislative changes have hit interim profits of Intercare, the
USM-traded supplier of healthcare products, prompting an 8p fall to 89p in
the share price yesterday.
At the pre-tax level, profits declined by 20 per cent to Pounds 1.34m in the
half year to end April, reflecting a 41 per cent drop in the mobility
division contribution to Pounds 430,000.
Mr Robert Shepherd, non-executive chairman, said that the legislation
changes had led to a downturn in scooter business and trading was likely to
continue to be affected in the second half.
For the group as a whole, he believed the first half pattern of trading was
likely to continue for the rest of the current year. In 1992-93 group profit
was Pounds 4.31m.
Group turnover rose from Pounds 17.7m to Pounds 20.5m, while earnings per
share came out at 3.25p (4.1p).
The interim dividend is unchanged at 0.7p.
</TEXT>
