<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Exceptional puts London &amp; Metropolitan in
the black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London &amp; Metropolitan, the property developer that was forced into a second
financial restructuring last year, yesterday announced a pre-tax profit of
Pounds 10.2m for 1993, compared with a loss of Pounds 19.6m incurred in the
previous year.
Profits were buoyed by a Pounds 20.2m exceptional item as a result of the
restructuring, primarily from the write-back of provisions.
However, the company remains hampered by its sole overseas project, the Pont
Royal resort in southern France. L&amp;M made a Pounds 7.7m provision against
its share of the cost of the project, reflecting disappointing sales during
1993.
The directors said the company was in better shape following its latest
restructuring, a debt-for-equity swap. Debts were down by Pounds 54m to
Pounds 73.3m, and negative shareholders funds amounted to Pounds 4.93m,
against a negative Pounds 60.33m in 1992.
Mr Chris Harris, chairman, said: 'We've got the company back to a position
where we can now take advantage of opportunities coming out of the
improvement in the UK market.'
However, its problems are not over. The company was brought to the brink by
its involvement in the collapsed consortium to redevelop County Hall, and
its joint venture development of Pont Royal remains critical.
L&amp;M is carrying Pounds 45m of floating rate debt from its exposure to the
French project, and sales last year did not cover interest costs.
In the UK, business was said to be looking better. L&amp;M is project manager
for Value Retail, which plans a number of US-style factory outlet shopping
centres.
The first, in Bicester, will open in spring 1995 and Mr Harris said it was
25 per cent pre-let, with a further 50 per cent at an advanced stage of
negotiation.
L&amp;M has an option to take a 15 per cent stake in the company.
Overall, the group's UK operations contributed operating profits of Pounds
2.5m for the year, while interest costs were were reduced from Pounds 12.46m
to Pounds 4.79m.
</TEXT>
