<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / Sprint/EDS drop Dollars 30bn merger after value dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KANSAS CITY, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sprint, the US telecommunications group, and Electronic Data Systems, the
world's largest computing services company, said yesterday they had
abandoned negotiations for a Dollars 30bn (Pounds 20bn) merger but were
still exploring other forms of strategic relationship.
The merger failed, according to sources close to the negotiations, because
of a disagreement over the value of Sprint, the third largest US long
distance operator, which is believed still to be seeking an alliance with a
European telecoms group. It has had talks with the French and German state
telecoms operators. One source claimed yesterday that potential European
partners had been contemplating an equity investment in Sprint or the
combined Sprint/EDS.
The collapse of the merger talks came three weeks after the two companies
announced they were in discussions which might have led to the creation of
an information services powerhouse, with a market capitalisation of Dollars
30bn and annual revenues of more than Dollars 20bn.
This is the latest multi-billion dollar engagement called off between
companies in the converging US industries of telecoms, cable television and
computing. The immediate reason was money. The proposal involved EDS
shareholders getting one new share in the combined company for every EDS
share. EDS thought Sprint shareholders should get 1.1 shares in the new
business, while Sprint demanded 1.3.
EDS is a subsidiary of General Motors. To help the merger negotiations, GM
said it would consider spinning off EDS. GM said yesterday it would continue
to consider a spin-off if such a move would help EDS 'attain its strategic
objectives'.
