<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / BAA to double airport investment to Pounds 1.4bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAA, the privatised UK airports group, yesterday announced plans to double
capital spending to Pounds 1.4bn over the next three years after reporting a
13 per cent rise in annual pre-tax profits to Pounds 322m.
Revenues rose 15.3 per cent to Pounds 1.1bn in the year to March. The strong
performance coupled with a proposed one-for-one scrip issue helped push up
BAA shares 11p to 949p yesterday.
Although income from regulated airport charges was virtually flat at Pounds
368m, reflecting the Civil Aviation Authority's price control formula, net
retail income rose by 7.6 per cent to Pounds 328m with passengers spending
on average 5 per cent more in airport shops.
Retailing is increasingly becoming a prime source of income for BAA and is
expected eventually to overtake revenues from regulated airport charges.
The big increase in capital spending reflected the need to cope with
expanding air travel in the UK. 'By the turn of the century, we are
expecting nearly a third more people to fly through our London airports than
at present,' said Sir John Egan, BAA's chief executive.
Passengers using BAA's airports increased 5.6 per cent last year to 82m,
with 71.5m using the three London airports of Heathrow, Gatwick and
Stansted. Sir John said passenger traffic was continuing to grow by around
5.5 per cent this year, confirming the economic recovery. Overall, BAA is
forecasting annual growth of around 4 per cent until the end of the century.
Sir John argued that Heathrow's planned Terminal 5 was 'vital' for BAA, the
UK aviation industry and the UK economy. He said recent estimates suggested
that more than 180,000 jobs were generated by economic activity at Heathrow
airport.
BAA was confident it could finance its ambitious investment programme from
its own cash and borrowings.
'Our key ratios have continued to improve, with interest cover rising to 4.8
and gearing falling to 28.5 per cent,' said Mr Nigel Ellis, finance
director. 'We will ensure that we have the capacity to build Terminal 5
without the need for a rights issue.'
However, he said cash flow, which was positive last year, would be negative
this year with the higher capital spending. Debt is expected to start
rising.
BAA is proposing a final dividend of 11.25p, giving a total for the year of
18p, a 12.5 per cent increase on the previous year's 16p. Earnings per share
rose 12.7 per cent to 47p (41.7p).
The company is also proposing to introduce a scrip dividend to allow
shareholders to take their dividend payments in shares instead of cash.
Lex, Page 20; Capital spending details, Page 22
</TEXT>
