<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / Health climbdown on coal sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The government announced a significant climbdown on coal privatisation
yesterday when it said it would retain responsibility for health and injury
claims resulting from service with British Coal before privatisation.
Its decision, confirmed by Lord Strathclyde, a trade and industry minister,
follows pressure from potential buyers of the corporation who said they
would be deterred from bidding unless the government capped the illness
liabilities.
Yesterday's announcement leaves outstanding differences between the
government and prospective bidders over other liabilities including
subsidence and pollution.
However, the illness issue was the most significant of the differences.
Previously the government had suggested that new owners of the industry
would have to pick up the entire bill for future claims even if some of the
illness related to a period when the worker was in British Coal's
employment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
