<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / Minford fears threat to Scots councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government plans to scrap Scotland's two-tier system of local government
will reduce the Scottish economy's ability to compete internationally and
could lead to chaos, Professor Patrick Minford said yesterday.
Prof Minford, a rightwing economist and one of the panel of 'wise men' who
advise the Treasury, said large local authorities were needed to take
strategic planning decisions involving such things as roads, factories and
airports.
The costs of such projects were heavily concentrated in a particular
locality whereas the benefits were spread widely. Planning powers given to
small local councils to block development on 'not in my backyard' grounds
would limit Scotland's ability to compete for inward investment.
Prof Minford was in Glasgow addressing businessmen and councillors invited
by Labour-dominated Strathclyde regional council, which is fighting
government plans to replace it and its 19 district councils with 12 unitary
authorities under the Scottish local government reform bill going through
parliament.
Prof Minford said the government seemed to be interested only in councils
delivering services efficiently to the consumer rather than in their
strategic planning role. Chaos was 'an apposite word' to use to describe the
results of the government's policy.
Arguing for a two-tier system, he pointed to the crucial role South
Glamorgan county council, soon to be abolished, had played in overruling
Vale of Glamorgan district council to secure the location of a Bosch plant
which now employs 1,000 people.
By contrast, the economy of Merseyside was declining because of the
inability of councils to agree following the abolition of the metropolitan
authority in 1986.
</TEXT>
