<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / Major's man in Dorset plays the multi-speed card: John
Authers finds allegations of dirty tricks have arisen in a closely fought
Euro-seat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bryan Cassidy, Tory MEP for the Liberal Democrat target seat of Dorset
and East Devon, is clear about his attitude to Europe. 'I'm a Euro-sceptic,'
he says, 'but not a Europhobe.'
The distinction is important, he says, and lies at the heart of his campaign
to hold on to the seat.
His aim is to enthuse voters about Europe's importance, and the potential
for local benefits - increasing the chance that they will turn out to vote -
while also tapping distrust of the Brussels bureaucracy.
Mr John Major's call for a 'multi-speed' Europe suited Mr Cassidy and he is
quick to mention it to voters as his campaign Land Rover blares Beethoven's
Ode to Joy, the European anthem.
Keeping the campaign on European issues is the only way to avoid turning the
election into a referendum on Mr Major's record at Westminster, and the
'multi-speed Europe' position, says Mr Cassidy, is one the party can defend
on the doorstep.
The Liberal Democrats are emphasising local issues. Last week saw the launch
of a petition against the closure of rural post offices. Mr Philip
Goldenberg, the candidate, has also helped to collect a petition against
value added tax on fuel.
Lib Dem election literature stresses Conservative 'broken promises' on VAT,
income tax, education and the National Health Service. Meanwhile the party's
national figures, including Mr Paddy Ashdown, the leader, make regular
visits.
There have even been allegations of dirty tricks. Mr Goldenberg reported Mr
Cassidy to the European Court of Auditors for 'alleged misuse of public
money for electioneering purposes', while Mr Cassidy has complained of
'political hoodlums' stealing his poster boards.
On paper, Dorset and East Devon is one of the Liberal Democrats' best hopes
of victory. The party won Dorset County Council last year, and opinion polls
predict that it will win the seat. Christchurch, scene of a sweeping
by-election victory last year, was within the seat until its boundaries were
redrawn earlier this year.
But Dorset is not as fertile territory for the party as the Somerset and
Cornwall Euro-seats, both of which have two Liberal Democrat MPs. All the
Dorset Euro-seat's seven Westminster constituencies are held comfortably by
Conservatives, and most of it is untouched by South West Water's high
charges, which provoke bitter opposition further west.
Socially, the seat resembles the Conservative heartlands of the Home
Counties and the south coast more than it does the non-conformist west
country. Apart from the conurbation of Bournemouth and Poole, the towns are
predominantly agricultural market towns, while many residents in the east of
the county are retired pensioners from the Home Counties.
Mr Cassidy encountered plenty of anger on the placid streets of Bridport
last week, but most of it - perhaps because the Ode to Joy was playing in
the background - was directed at Europe, not at Mr Major.
An elderly gentleman, asked if he would vote Tory, said: 'I don't think so
somehow, not this time. I'm very anti-Common Market. It's cost me too much
money.'
He said he would vote for the 'anti-Common Market candidate'. There are two,
a Conservative Anti-Federalist and the UK Independence party.
A traffic warden was angrier: 'We're listening to people in Brussels telling
us what to do. It interferes with me in my life, in what I have to buy. They
try to stop us making our own cider and farmhouse cheese.' Mr Cassidy
dismissed these as 'media myths'.
Out on the stump, talking about Europe, the seat appears safe for the
Tories, and yet there is a perceptible air of unease about the campaign.
They know that if Dorset did opt for the Lib Dems, no special local factors
could be blamed as would be possible in Cornwall or Somerset. It would be an
unambiguous vote of protest against the Conservative government.
One Tory-voting local businessman articulated the concern: 'How are you
going to get people to vote for you on Europe as opposed to what they've
seen in the country as a whole?'
He added: 'As far as Westminster is concerned, there's been a lot of
incompetence, I would suggest. It's unprofessional at best.'
</TEXT>
