<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / Gummer reopens Tory split
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, yesterday reopened the divisions
over Europe in Mr John Major's cabinet by taking a markedly different
approach from the prime minister to the future of the European Union.
As Labour sought to highlight what it called the Tory party's 'great divide'
over Europe, Mr Gummer hinted at discontent in the cabinet about Mr Major's
recent commitment to a 'multi-speed' EU.
With the European elections only two days away, the prime minister has
elaborated on a 'new vision' for Europe, in which member states can decide
'in their own way and at their own speed' how much power they give to
Brussels.
But Mr Gummer - one of the most pro-European ministers - yesterday warned
that it would be 'quite unacceptable' if the development of more flexible
decision making allowed Britain to take a more cautious line on its place in
Europe.
'What is absolutely clear is that Britain is not going to be at a slower
speed than the rest of Europe,' he said at the Tories' daily Euro-election
news conference. 'We are at the heart of Europe and we have no intention of
being at a slower speed than the others.'
Mr Gummer also appeared to disagree with the prime minister on why flexible
decision making needed to be introduced in the first place.
Last week Mr Major claimed that the 'multi-speed, multi-track' idea should
be an integral part of the EU's development into the next century.
But yesterday Mr Gummer cast that theme in more modest terms, claiming that
it would merely relate to new applications for EU membership from the
developing countries of eastern Europe.
He said: 'A number of countries who want to join cannot just join on the
basis of total access. What the prime minister is suggesting is that you
have got to look at ways in which we enable people to join at a different
level.'
Labour claimed that the prime minister was trying to manage irreconcilable
division between pro and anti-Europeans in his party.
Mr Jack Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, said: 'So deeply split is the
Conservative party now on Europe that its leader is obliged himself to face
both ways on just about every important issue.'
He said that the prime minister had become 'the modern embodiment of Janus:
a split personality chairing a split cabinet, leading a split party'.
Mr Cunningham singled out Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, who so
far has played no part in the campaign, saying that sending him to France
had failed to keep the 'rift' in Tory ranks out of the headlines 'let alone
to heal it'.
For the Liberal Democrats, Sir Russell Johnston, Europe spokesman, said the
Tory campaign had been 'wholly negative' and had sought to maximise
differences.
Mr John Major's rhetoric had not 'openly mirrored' the condemnation of
foreigners expressed by Euro-sceptic cabinet ministers such as Mr Michael
Portillo and Mr Lilley, Sir Russell said. But 'the meaning has been the same
and they have never been disowned'.
Sir Russell was supported by Lord Thomson of Monifieth, a former EU
commissioner, who said it was a 'heartbreaking tragedy' that the Tories had
turned their back on playing a key role in the EU 'for reasons of purely
domestic politics'.
</TEXT>
