<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / Leadership Contest: Beckett seems likely to stand:
Leadership contest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party's leadership election is likely to be a three-horse race
between Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, Mr John Prescott, shadow
employment secretary, and Mrs Margaret Beckett, the party's leader. Mrs
Beckett is not certain to stand yet, in spite of strong pressure to put her
name forward from feminist and traditionalist Labour MPs. But friends say
she is increasingly likely to run for the leadership and the deputy
leadership.
Mrs Beckett, who is said by many MPs to have performed creditably as party
leader since John Smith died last month, has told friends that she wants to
do the job permanently. She believes that her position may help her to
overhaul Mr Tony Blair, the runaway favourite, over the six-week campaign
that will start on Friday.
Her supporters think her prospects of winning would be boosted significantly
by endorsement from outside her base on the left.
The key target is Mr Bill Morris, leader of the TGWU general union, which
sponsors Mrs Beckett.
Supporters are also seeking endorsement from Mr John Edmonds, leader of the
GMB general union, which has invited the potential candidates to address an
informal gathering of its annual conference on Monday.
Mrs Beckett's emergence as a serious candidate for the leadership
complicates the options for Mr Prescott, whose support is also mainly on the
left of the party.
Mr Prescott is thought unlikely to stand for both the leadership and deputy
leadership because of the fear that his leadership bid would be regarded as
less than serious.
Most Labour MPs think Mrs Beckett's role as the continuity candidate makes
her certain to be re-elected deputy leader - even if she contests the
leadership as well.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, is still gauging his
support, but is thought unlikely to stand.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
