<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / Peers pledge to oppose core of de-regulation bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's bill to cut regulatory burdens on business faces a
difficult passage through the House of Lords, opposition and Conservative
backbench peers indicated last night.
Labour and Liberal Democrat peers made clear that they would mount a
determined bid to remove core provisions in the bill, which would allow the
government to short-circuit parliamentary procedures in abolishing
regulations.
Lord Peston, chief Labour spokesman on the de-regulation and contracting-out
bill, denounced as a 'constitutional outrage' the government's proposal to
abolish regulations using parliamentary orders. The orders are subject to
short debates and cannot be amended whereas primary legislation is subject
to the full parliamentary process.
Lord Rodgers of Quarry Bank, for the Liberal Democrats, described the
provisions as 'outrageous'.
Lord Cockfield, the Conservative peer and former cabinet minister, also
criticised the growth in ministerial power at the expense of parliament.
He urged ministers not to be mesmerised by the catchphrase 'de-regulation'.
Assurances by Lord Strathclyde, the minister in charge of the bill, that the
bill's 'exceptional' powers would be subject to new safeguards in the
Commons as well as the Lords, failed to satisfy the critics.
Lord Peston called on peers to delete the provisions from the bill and force
the Commons to think again. 'If we do not do that I cannot see what
justification there is for us being here at all.'
From the non-party cross benches Lord Bancroft, a former head of the civil
service, said the process of dismantling the public service through the
transfer of functions to agencies subject to very limited parliamentary
control and debate had gone too far.
Lord Beloff, the Conservative peer and academic, said the
'professionalisation of politics' had reduced MPs of all parties to lobby
fodder.
Lord Clinton-Davis, in the final speech from the opposition front bench,
reaffirmed that if the bill became law it would be repealed by the next
Labour government.
The bill was given an unopposed second reading.
</TEXT>
