<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / UK consumer borrowing slips but trend is firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Borrowing by British consumers fell back slightly in April but the figures
were welcomed in the City where it has been feared spending was growing too
quickly.
However, the trend over three months remains strongly upwards suggesting the
UK is on track for a healthy recovery.
Net lending to consumers through finance houses, bank credit cards with the
Visa and Mastercard system and non-mortgage building society loans fell to a
seasonally adjusted Pounds 413m in April, down from Pounds 518m the previous
month.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday the figures may have been
distorted by the timing of the Easter holiday, which fell in both March and
April, and stressed that three-monthly figures were a better guide to the
trend.
These showed that net lending reached record levels in the three months to
April, running at Pounds 1.282bn. The level of new credit advanced to
consumers in that period was also a record, at Pounds 15.105bn.
The figures were welcomed by the Treasury, which suggested they provided
hints that consumer borrowing had not yet been dented by April's tax rises.
'It is too early to say what the full impact of the tax increases will be.
But clearly it is encouraging that the trend remains upwards - this is
consistent with an upward trend in consumer spending,' a spokesman said.
The figures also received a warm reception among City analysts, who noted
that April's dip followed an exceptionally strong level of consumer credit
in March.
Analysts had predicted April's net lending figure could fall as low as
Pounds 300m, after a survey by the Finance and Leasing Association earlier
this week reported a small drop in consumer credit in April.
Mr Simon Briscoe, UK economist with investment bank SG Warburg, said: 'This
is almost the perfect set of numbers for the government and markets. It
shows that the recovery is continuing but not overheating - it would be
difficult to argue for a base rate rise on these figures.'
But with the economic figures still painting a slightly uneven picture of
consumer behaviour, analysts warned it was too early to predict the full
impact of the April tax rises.
Although recent retail sales and narrow money supply figures have pointed to
strong consumer activity, housing figures have suggested a slowdown in
mortgage lending.
Consumer confidence surveys have also pointed to relatively muted levels of
confidence - a factor that may be feeding through to consumer borrowing
figures.
The main factor in the drop in April's net lending figure was a fall in
borrowing from finance houses, the form of finance normally used to buy cars
and large consumer goods, such as fridges.
Car credit, which represents about half of total finance house lending, fell
to Pounds 871m in April, its lowest level since October. This was partly
offset by other data released yesterday, which showed car sales rebounded
sharply in May, after weakening earlier in the year.
Finance lending dips, Page 9
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
<XX>
