<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / International Company News: Alexander &amp; Alexander trade
halted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Alexander &amp; Alexander, the US-based insurance broker, were
suspended from trading in New York yesterday pending what it promised early
in the day would be a 'significant corporate announcement', writes Richard
Waters in New York.
By late afternoon, though, the company's board, which had been convened for
a special meeting, remained locked in debate and had failed to make any
public statement.
The company's recent financial difficulties, and the nature of its
announcement in the morning, prompted widespread speculation that it had
become the subject of a takeover approach. Its shares have slid from Dollars
22 1/4 on February 3, the day before Federal Reserve action to raise US
interest rates hit all financial sector stocks, to Dollars 14 in mid-May,
before recovering slightly to Dollars 16 3/8 by the end of last week.
The world's second largest insurance broker behind Marsh &amp; McLennan,
Alexander &amp; Alexander's earnings have consistently failed to match stock
market expectations in recent periods. The company has also suffered big
losses in liability insurance. In January, the company's board acted to
replace long-time chairman and chief executive Mr Tinsely Irvin.
</TEXT>
