<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / International Company News: Litigation costs accountants
Dollars 1.1bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Litigation last year cost the big US accounting firms over Dollars 1bn for
the first time, according to figures published by the six biggest firms. The
amount, just short of Dollars 1.1bn, compares with Dollars 783m the year
before and is made up of judgments, out-of-court settlements and legal
defence costs, writes Richard Waters.
Publication of the figures, for which no detailed breakdown was given, is
part a campaign by accountants in the US for legislative reform to limit
their exposure to malpractice suits.
Most of the increased costs last year were met by insurance. Payments from
insurance companies (after deducting premiums) came to Dollars 416m, up from
Dollars 185m in 1992 and only Dollars 8m in 1991. After insurance
recoveries, litigation costs amounted to 12 per cent of their accounting and
audit fees, according to the firms - Arthur Andersen, Coopers &amp; Lybrand,
Deloitte &amp; Touche, Ernst &amp; Young, KPMG Peat Marwick and Price Waterhouse.
</TEXT>
