<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Company News (This Week): Worries surface as Swatch marks
time - SMH
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SMH, the Swiss watchmaking group best known for the Swatch, will receive
journalists and investment analysts at its annual results presentations
tomorrow in Berne.
In contrast to the festive mood of the last two presentations - following
profit rises of 32 and 64 per cent - tomorrow's affair is likely to be
sober, possibly even quarrelsome.
The SMH bearer share has lost a third of its value in the past year in
response to unfavourable rumours and developments that have not yet been
fully explained by the group's usually voluble chairman, Mr Nicolas Hayek.
Fears that Swatch sales were stagnating appeared to be confirmed in February
when the group announced flat sales for 1993 of SFr2.86bn (Pounds 1.4bn) and
net income up only 7 per cent to SFr440m. Although SMH makes several other
highly profitable brands, including Omega and Blancpain, Swatch provides the
vital volume.
Meanwhile, SMH's strategy of applying the Swatch brand name to other
consumer products is looking a bit frayed.
The withdrawal of the industrialist Mr Stephan Schmidheiny from the
controlling shareholder pool has sharpened suspicions that Mr Hayek prefers
to run the group single-handed. Many analysts wonder if he is putting in
enough effort to secure the group's place in the post-Swatch mass market.
</TEXT>
