<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Company News (This Week): Long distance call in place
despite local difficulties - Vodafone
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The mobile communications group Vodafone has been pushed off its pedestal,
its shares falling from an all-time peak of 637p in February to 517p at the
end of last week. But analysts expect its 1993-94 pre-tax profits, due for
release tomorrow, to be in the range of Pounds 350m-Pounds 370m and its
medium-term prospects are still seen as healthy.
At Pounds 360m, Robert Fleming's mid-way projection, Vodafone would be 12
per cent ahead of last year's Pounds 322m, with earnings per share of 24.2p
up 9 per cent. 'The UK cellular market is becoming more competitive, but
Vodafone is holding its own,' says Mr Kevin Langford, Fleming's mobile
communications analyst. 'The main concern is about prospects for its new
digital networks and the expansion of its overseas business.'
Vodafone's shares have been depressed by the recent malaise in the telecoms
sector, with added volatility caused by the launch of two new national
cellular networks in the last eight months - Mercury One-2-One and Hutchison
Microtel's Orange. None the less, Vodafone enjoyed record numbers of new
connections in both December and March, and now boasts 1.2m UK subscribers.
Slow growth in its new UK digital networks has not mattered while capacity
on the analogue network remained abundant, but analysts are looking for
evidence of a viable Vodafone strategy to move customers across to its
enhanced - but more expensive - GSM digital network.
Vodafone is well on the way to realising its goal of acquiring overseas
franchises with an aggregate population equal to the UK, adjusting for
income and the company's share of consortia. But it has yet to make much
return on overseas investments.
</TEXT>
