FT  06 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Reporters on local newspapers spend their lives doodling in their notebooks
while waiting for the bench to return in magistrates' courts; doodling in
their notebooks while waiting for parish councillors to come out of closed
session; and urging the secretary of the WI to remember who won the 'Most
objects in a matchbox' competition this week. And yet - surprise, surprise -
when Michael Palin finally fulfils a boyhood ambition and joins the staff of
the Isle of Wight County Press, what is his first assignment? Occult
rituals, of course. Still, Palin is an engaging presenter and director Roger
Mills has a good track record, so Palin's Column should be entertaining
(8.00 C4). BBC1 fights D-Day all over again, with a two-hour slab in the
morning and four hours in the afternoon. The evening session begins at 7.00
with a 60-minute 'nostalgic tribute' of words and music called We'll Meet
Again. From 9.40 there is commemorative material, beginning with News 44 in
which Sue Lawley presents the news of 50 years ago today as though it were
happening now.
