<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Call for tax curb on forex
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Foreign exchange speculators should be taxed to curb their influence on
international markets, says Professor James Tobin, a Nobel prize-winning
economist at Yale University.
Writing in New Economy, the journal of the centre-left Institute for Public
Policy Research, he describes speculation on currencies as a 'threat to
rational policies' and proposes putting 'sand in the wheels' of currency
markets.
Prof Tobin says that the tax would 'direct traders' attention to long-run
fundamentals and away from contagious but transient market sentiment'.
His views were in part contradicted in speech by Mr Eddie George, governor
of the Bank of England, at the weekend. He told the Forex 94 conference in
London that 'there is a popular misperception of the foreign exchange
markets as a huge, single-minded pack of wolves, acting in unison to hunt
down and destroy one largely defenceless currency after another in an
insatiable lust for short-term profit'.
Conceding that free capital movements, and short-term speculators, could
complicate the life of central bankers, Mr George went on: 'But there are
legions of others, who look . . . like speculators, often managing other
people's funds, who are seeking to protect the value of the assets they
control against losses, by diversifying risks or covering their currency
exposures.'
</TEXT>
