<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Major hangs campaign on integration fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday launched a last-ditch attempt to stave off disaster
for the Conservatives in Thursday's European elections by stepping up his
attack on the dangers of greater European integration.
The prime minister used a wide-ranging television interview to emphasise
that his 'instincts' were not in favour of a single European currency and to
predict that the European Union would 'break' if it did not develop more
flexibly.
Pressed on his own future Mr Major said that the government had a five-year
programme and he expected to carry it through. It would be 'perfectly
proper' for someone to use the party's leadership procedure to mount a
challenge in the autumn. If that happened 'I will take on whomsoever the
contestant may be and I would hope and expect to beat that contestant'.
He said he would 'pick my own time' for the cabinet reshuffle, expected
during the summer. This would not be affected in any way by the date of the
coming Labour leadership election.
But, as the main parties reduced the intensity of their Euro-election
campaigning to accommodate yesterday's commemoration of the D-day landings,
Mr Major declined to predict the election's result.
A recent opinion poll put the Conservatives in third place more than 30
percentage points behind Labour, suggesting the party could be reduced to a
handful of seats.
Such a result, coming within a month of the Tories' local election
humiliation, would revive doubts about Mr Major's leadership and bring
renewed speculation that a challenge to the prime minister could be mounted
this autumn.
The Conservatives hold 32 seats in the European parliament compared with 45
for Labour. A haul of fewer than a dozen seats this time would be regarded
as a serious setback for Mr Major.
Interviewed on BBC-TV's Frost on Sunday, the prime minister said that to
argue for the flexibility of a 'multi-speed' Europe, as he did at a rally at
Ellesmere Port last week, was not to argue against the EU.
Europe had 'slowly, unobtrusively' been moving in that direction for some
time. The EU had to develop 'in a more flexible way', he said. 'I believe if
it doesn't then it will break.'
Sir David Steel, foreign affairs spokesman for the Liberal Democrats,
attacked the government for being 'shackled' by the Euro-sceptics on its own
back benches.
Labour concentrated its assault on tax, where it hopes the primary focus of
the campaign will rest in the approach to polling day.
</TEXT>
