<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Defence unions voice job worries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions representing workers in the defence sector are trying to use the
European election campaign to focus attention on the prospect of tens of
thousands of job losses.
They are challenging the government's claim that support services can be
trimmed without affecting defence capacity, and accusing ministers of
delaying the announcement of sweeping changes in an attempt to reduce the
political cost.
Mr Jack Dromey, national secretary for public services at the TGWU general
union, said: 'Ministers are concealing catastrophe until after the
elections.'
He believes job losses in the defence sector could be a crucial issue in at
least one Lancashire constituency, and throughout the south-west, a
Conservative stronghold with strong military and naval associations.
The unions hope that raising the jobs issue during the election campaign
will deflect the government from postponing a controversial announcement
until just before the summer recess.
Mr Dromey said: 'They must not be allowed to frustrate parliamentary
scrutiny and proper consultation by announcing major cuts to Britain's
defence capacity, and tens of thousands of job losses, just as MPs are
disappearing to Tuscany.'
Mr John Clark, head of the Ministry of Defence section at the NUCPS civil
service union, said the unions wanted a 'proper strategic review' of
military spending. He said: 'The government is trying to carve out a new
imperial role for itself by interfering in wars across the world, yet no
consideration is being given to the infrastructure of our economy or
Britain's own defence needs.'
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, has promised a statement soon on
the results of the Defence Costs Studies, an effort to trim Pounds 750m from
the ministry's budget without compromising military capability.
At least 33 studies are in progress, and the proposals are understood to
include closing several ministry buildings in London, shutting Royal Navy
and Royal Air Force staff colleges and cutting the forces' in-house capacity
in areas such as transport, medical care and weapons maintenance.
The MoD trade unions expect 15,000 civilian and 10,000 military posts to be
shed as an immediate result of the DCS, and they are urging members to raise
the issue with all European election candidates.
</TEXT>
