<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Prescott targets full employment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Prescott, the most likely 'traditionalist' candidate for the Labour
leadership, is preparing to put full employment at the centre of his
leadership campaign.
The shadow employment secretary - who refuses to say whether he will run
until after Thursday's European elections - is widely expected to declare
his candidacy the next day.
Such a move would pit him against Mr Tony Blair, the leading Labour
'moderniser' and overwhelming favourite to succeed John Smith as leader.
Other candidates may include Mrs Margaret Beckett, the party's present
leader.
Friends of Mr Prescott say the pugnacious MP for Hull East would use a
leadership campaign to press for a much clearer definition of what the
party's commitment to full employment means.
They say he believes that full employment could be turned into the main
issue of the campaign.
Ten days ago Mr Prescott called for a return to the socialist values of the
1945 Labour government in a speech that was billed as the launch of his
leadership campaign.
Last week he said he thought there should be a contest, arguing that an
election was 'an essential part of the democratic process'.
This view is thought to be shared by Mr Blair, whose supporters see a
contest - which they are convinced he would win - as an invaluable means of
shoring up his authority.
The Blair camp has been anxious to let it be known that unsuccessful
challengers would not be punished for opposing him.
They have stressed that no promises have been given to any colleagues
regarding specific future shadow cabinet positions under Mr Blair.
This includes Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor and close confidant of
Mr Blair, who decided to stand aside from the race last week.
It also emerged yesterday that Mr Blair might delay the formal announcement
of his candidacy until early next week rather than on Friday, when
nominations open.
Such a move would avoid attention being diverted from the European election
results, which could be very favourable for Labour.
</TEXT>
