<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / House conditions 'alarming'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One in 13 homes in the UK is unfit for human habitation under official
criteria, says a report published today to mark the start of National
Housing Week. It says at least Pounds 22bn is needed to deal with urgent
repairs.
The National Housing Forum, an umbrella organisation representing a range of
organisations involved in housing, says the rate of demolition is so slow
that properties now being built will need to last 4,000 years - the age of
Stonehenge. The forum says one in six homes needs urgent repairs costing
more than Pounds 1,000. Urgent repairs are those that would lead to further
substantial damage if not tackled, including water leaks, serious dampness
or dangerous wiring.
The report warns that housing conditions have reached alarming levels, with
the majority of homes in poor condition being owner-occupied.
It calls for an increase in the rate of demolition of unsound and
substandard properties. The rate has fallen from more than 80,000 properties
a year at the start of the 1970s to fewer than 5,000 in 1991-92.
It recommends that owner-occupiers who cannot afford to repair their homes
should be helped with equity-sharing loans and social security payments.
Building societies and other lenders should be more active in encouraging
borrowers to keep their homes in good condition, it says.
Papering over the Cracks: Housing Conditions and the Nation's Health.
National Housing Forum, 35 Great Smith Street, London SW1P 3BJ. Pounds 12.
</TEXT>
