<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Selling beer for a smoked-salmon life: Motoko Rich and
William Lewis on the trade driving brewers into disagreement with the
Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH and WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the hot, dusty car park of a warehouse less than a mile from the Calais
ferry port in France three British men loaded 40 cases of German lager into
a tatty red van.
As they shoved boxes between plastic bags of duty-free whisky and wine they
traded insults and braggadacio with the staff of EastEnders, a cash and
carry which caters to bulk buyers. 'This lot will all be gone tomorrow,' a
twenty-something man boasted.
Identified only as Ernie, he lurched forward and declared: 'I make bundles
of money. You want to know how much? Think smoked salmon on Friday, veal on
Sunday.' His friend, about 30-years-old with freckles, a visible belly and a
fading tattoo, talked specifics. 'We sell it around and it's Pounds 1,000 a
week for each of us,' he said. 'It's hard work, but it's worth it.'
These men, and others like them - including an 11-man gang from Cardiff
whose three ringleaders were jailed last week - are taking advantage of the
mammoth duty differential between the UK and France.
A duty ratio of seven to one on beer, nearly 50 to one on wine and just over
two to one on spirits has prompted them to shuttle between the UK and the
Continent to bring back alcohol for re-sale at home.
Such activities have initiated a growing rift between brewers and the
government. Mr Robin Simpson, director of the Brewers and Licensed
Retailers' Association, says the duty differential provides a 'direct
incentive to organised crime'.
Brewers claim sales of smuggled beer are eroding the British drinks market
at the rate of Pounds 1bn a year. They also say the illegal trade costs the
Treasury Pounds 40m a year in beer duty and value added tax alone.
These industry protests have met with scepticism at the Treasury. Sir John
Cope, the paymaster-general, said: 'There has not so far been a
haemorrhaging of duty receipts.' In 1993, the first year of the single
market when travellers in the European Union could bring in alcohol up to
the level of personal consumption, revenue from alcohol duty was up, if only
by less than 1 per cent for beer receipts. Customs &amp; Excise estimates the
dutiable value of all undetected bootleg goods - beer, wine, spirits and
tobacco - at Pounds 35m. But Customs officers on the ground say their
policing efforts only 'touch on the subject' and anecdotes of a burgeoning
black market in excise goods are rife.
So how much is going on and how organised is it?
The recent conviction of the Cardiff gang, as well as a Wolverhampton trio
who admitted evading duty on alcohol and cigarettes worth more than Pounds
73,000 last month, has led to suspicions of a growing organised element.
But most of the stories - and the cases which Customs has dealt with -
concern small-time operators, unemployed or low-paid people trying to make
some extra money.
Mr Don Price, a senior Customs officer in south Wales, said: 'We believe the
entrepreneur type of bootlegger - the guy who hires a van and goes over to
France and then flogs the stuff around the council estates - is the most
prevalent at the moment.'
In two trips to Calais over the past two weeks we found that Transit vans,
assumed by brewers to be used primarily for carrying alcohol for re-sale in
the UK, comprised no more than 10 per cent of vehicles on ferries. One group
we met in Calais said they made the trip from the Isle of Dogs in London to
France or Belgium five times a week. One said: 'The key is having a buyer
lined up beforehand. I have a mate who goes on a milk round.'
John, another Londoner who travels regularly to France and brings back
vanloads of beer or wine to sell to friends and family, seems typical of the
illegal trade. He said: 'As far as I'm concerned it's not organised. It's
just off-the-cuff stuff. We are not great big cartels or anything like
that.'
Customs is keen, however, to crack any group trafficking excise goods on a
regular basis. Since the single market opened 250 excise verification
officers have been deployed to track the trade inland.
The officers make regular visits to clubs, pubs and off-licences looking for
proof of illegal sales. On a recent visit to a run-down workmen's club in
Barry, on the outskirts of Cardiff, three officers found only a one-litre
bottle of whisky and two 25cl bottles of cheap French lager.
Mr Charles Templing, one of the officers, said: 'All we have is a couple
bottles. What you want is cases of it.'
Customs has detected 1,588 cases of cross-channel smuggling to date. The
total revenue value of the goods seized amounts to Pounds 2.3m. The seized
alcohol and tobacco are stored in warehouses in 21 regions around the
country. In Cardiff, Customs has filled three rooms with contraband. In
Dover a week's worth of booty is stacked three feet deep in a 20 sq ft
confinement.
In spite of the volume of goods being seized, excise verification officers
believe there is much they cannot catch. Mr Noel Weare, an officer in south
Wales, said: 'The bootleggers are virtually getting away with it. Unless
Customs increases the enforcement role or decreases the duty then the
problem will increase. I do not think they realise the scale of this thing.'
The scale of the trade is vigorously disputed, but clearly there is some
hype involved. Mr Kostadinoski Goce, manager of a warehouse for Pidou, a
cash and carry in Calais, initially said about 50 vans a day now shopped at
Pidou, but when no vans appeared at his warehouse on our second trip to see
him he revised his estimate to 'anything between one and 25'. He said
business was at its height from October to December, when he claimed more
than 100 vans a day came to the warehouse, spending as much as Pounds 1,200
a vanload.
Mr Dave West, owner of EastEnders, said about 150 vans made a daily 'beer
run' to Calais. Around Christmas, he said, the traffic stepped up to more
than 1,000 vans a day. Many of his customers admitted to selling the
alcohol.
Mr West believes it is the hype, rather than the duty differential, which
has created the trade. 'Every time the brewers and Customs get worried about
it, they give it more publicity,' he said. 'Then the people who did not even
know it was cheaper over here get the idea to come over.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
