<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Brown to call for workers right to education leave
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gordon Brown will today call for all workers to be given a guaranteed
right to take leave of absence in order to study, as part of a 'permanent
education revolution' to tackle chronic unemployment.
The shadow chancellor will use a speech to the Institute of Public Policy
Research, the left-of-centre think-tank, to put education reform at the
centre of the party's fight to achieve full employment. Claiming that
'trickle-down economics' has failed, Mr Brown will argue that the missing
element in the battle against unemployment is a programme providing
opportunities for everyone to raise their skills.
Mr Brown will say that in seeking to develop such a programme Labour should
not flinch from facing difficult questions about potential new sources of
finance for investment in education and 'the way in which the growing
private education system affects educational opportunities'.
Among other measures Mr Brown will call for more nursery education for
under-fives; education for those aged 16 to 19 which provides 'parity of
esteem' for academic and vocational study and high-quality training for
school-leavers; and tax incentives for people who undertake their own
training.
</TEXT>
